4d656-e8fdc | 2026-07-10T13:33:55Z | session:4d65680c-ded1-47cd-a59a-4966eebe8eda | User: not rpc_who; that's too narrow -- it should be set to whatever sets the agent identity, not just `who` [...] Assistant: The right choke point is `resolve_session_inner` (`src/daemon/server/resolution.rs:107`), not `rpc_who`. Its terminal failure branches (lines 161-166 for `Strict`, 199-206 for `Channel`) are where every RPC handler that resolves caller identity — `who`, `chat_write`, `chat_read`, `propose`, `channels_create/edit/join/leave/switch`, `pty_send/attach`, `turn_start/check/end`, `invite`, `channel_add_member` (11 call sites total) — currently bails with "no active session, run session-start." \n  \n Registration itself is already centralized too: `rpc_session_start` (`session_start.rs:35`) → `Store::register_session` (`sessions.rs:93-150`), which today only fires from the harness's own SessionStart hook, with `agent_slug` taken verbatim from the hook payload — nothing server-side ever synthesizes it. \n  \n So the fix is one bridge: when `resolve_session_inner` hits its failure branch and no alias resolves, instead of bailing, synthesize an `agent_slug` (`<clientinfo-or-harness-name>/<random-suffix>`) and call `Store::register_session` before re-resolving — every caller in that list gets JIT identity for free, with no per-handler duplication.
4d656-84c25 | 2026-07-10T13:33:59Z | session:4d65680c-ded1-47cd-a59a-4966eebe8eda | - **HTTP** (`src/cli/mcp/http.rs`) — this is the one ChatGPT actually uses (the code even has a comment "ChatGPT requires HTTPS; tunnel this endpoint," line 65). Each POST is currently handled statelessly with **no session correlation at all** — no `Mcp-Session-Id` header is issued or read anywhere in `http.rs`. Per the MCP spec, `clientInfo` only arrives once, on `initialize`; without a session id to key a lookup by, a later `tools/call` from the same ChatGPT connection has no way to recover which `initialize` it belongs to. Threading `clientInfo.name` through for HTTP means first adding `Mcp-Session-Id` issuance/tracking (a small in-memory map + response header), which is a materially bigger change than "thread a field through." [...] - **`src/cli/mcp/http.rs`**: added `Mcp-Session-Id` tracking. On `initialize`, mints a session id (`mcp-<nanos>-<counter>`, matching the existing `mint_session_id()` convention), captures `clientInfo.name` from the request, stores it in a new `HttpState.mcp_sessions` map, and returns the id via the `Mcp-Session-Id` response header (also exposed/allowed via CORS). On every later request, reads the incoming `Mcp-Session-Id` header and looks up the stored name.
